    <h1 class="title" style="font-size:34px;">About Citizen Knowledge</h1>
  </header>

  <main>
    <p style="font-size:18px;">Citizen Knowledge is a companion project to <em>The Performance of Obedience: Legitimacy, Law, and the Systems We Pretend to Believe In</em>, by Greg Lewis, currently with UK literary agents.</p>
    <p style="font-size:18px;">The book argues that selective enforcement, not consistent rule-following, is how modern institutions actually operate: the same law, the same process, the same rule, applied differently depending on who it lands on. This project takes ordinary daily news stories and maps each one against that argument, showing which Part, Chapter, and sometimes subheading of the book the story illustrates.</p>

    <p style="font-size:18px;">Entries appear in three formats:</p>
    <ul style="font-size:17px;line-height:1.6;">
      <li><strong>Standard posts</strong> &mdash; a paraphrased summary of a news story, followed by a two-paragraph reframe mapping it to the book's argument.</li>
      <li><strong>Deep-read posts</strong> &mdash; marked with a Deep Read tag, these interleave the reframe with short, clearly-marked quotations from the manuscript itself.</li>
      <li><strong>Briefs</strong> &mdash; shorter entries for stories with a real but smaller angle: a gist, a compressed reframe, and a single book anchor, rather than the full two-paragraph treatment.</li>
    </ul>

    <p style="font-size:18px;">No images or verbatim text are reproduced from source publications. All summaries are original paraphrase, attributed by publication and date.</p>

